lessons.theory:
## Calling C from Rust
Rust can talk to other languages (mostly C). This is called FFI.

You have to use `extern "C"` to define the C functions you want to call, and you MUST call them inside an `unsafe` block because Rust can't guarantee that the C code is safe.

```rust
extern "C" {
    fn abs(input: i32) -> i32;
}

fn main() {
    unsafe {
        println!("Absolute value of -3 according to C: {}", abs(-3));
    }
}
```

lessons.starterCode:
extern "C" {
    fn ___(input: f64) -> f64;
}

fn main() {
    let number = 64.0;

    // Calling C code is unsafe!
    ___ {
        let result = ___(number);
        println!("Square root of {} is {}", number, result);
    }
}

lessons.solution:
extern "C" {
    fn sqrt(input: f64) -> f64;
}

fn main() {
    let number = 64.0;

    // Calling C code is unsafe!
    unsafe {
        let result = sqrt(number);
        println!("Square root of {} is {}", number, result);
    }
}

